    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</h4>
<p>Find a particular integral for the equation</p>
\[{@deq@}.\]
<p>\(y_\text{p}(x) = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>We are asked to find a particular integral for the second order, constant coefficients, inhomogeneous differential equation</p>
\[{@deq@}.\]
<p>Since the right-hand side is a linear term, we try a particular integral of the for \(y_\text{p}(x) = {@pitest@}\). We first find the derivatives:</p>
\[\begin{aligned}
\frac{\mathrm{d}y_\text{p}}{\mathrm{d}x} &amp;= {@dpitest@}, \\
\frac{\mathrm{d}^2y_\text{p}}{\mathrm{d}x^2} &amp;= {@ddpitest@}.
\end{aligned}\]
<p>Substituting these into the original equation gives</p>
\[{@pieq@}.\]
<p>Equating the constant terms and the coefficients of \(x\) gives the simultaneous equations</p>
\[\begin{cases}
{@lhs(pieq1)@} &amp;= {@rhs(pieq1)@} \\
{@lhs(pieq2)@} &amp;= {@rhs(pieq2)@}
\end{cases}\]
<p>These give the values \(a = {@aval@}\) and \(b = {@bval@}\). Hence, a particular integral for the differential equation is</p>
\[y_\text{p}(x) = {@pi1@}.\]]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
